<div class='bookAuthorProfile__about'>

<span id="freeTextContainer17973147736412024614">Nicole Krauss is the author of the international bestseller <i>The History of Love</i>, which was published by W.W. Norton in 2005. It won the William Saroyan International Prize for Writing, France’s Prix du Meilleur Livre Ėtranger, was named #1 book of the year by Amazon.com, and was short-listed for the Orange, Médicis, and Femina prizes. Her first novel, <i>Man Walks Into a Room</i>, was a finalist for the </span>
  <span id="freeText17973147736412024614" style="display:none">Nicole Krauss is the author of the international bestseller <i>The History of Love</i>, which was published by W.W. Norton in 2005. It won the William Saroyan International Prize for Writing, France’s Prix du Meilleur Livre Ėtranger, was named #1 book of the year by Amazon.com, and was short-listed for the Orange, Médicis, and Femina prizes. Her first novel, <i>Man Walks Into a Room</i>, was a finalist for the Los Angeles Times Book Award for First Fiction. In 2007, she was selected as one of Granta’s Best Young American Novelists, and in 2010 <i>The New Yorker</i> named her one of the 20 best writers under 40. <br /><br />Her fiction has been published in <i>The New Yorker</i>, <i>Harper’s</i>, <i>Esquire</i>, and <i>Best American Short Stories</i>, and her books have been translated into more than thirty-five languages. She recently completed a Cullman Fellowship at the New York Public Library. She lives in Brooklyn, New York.<br /><br />Find her here on Facebook: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://www.facebook.com/pages/Nicole-Krauss/141967625823841">http://www.facebook.com/pages/Nicole-...</a></span>
